.SH "PROCESS SCHEDULING PRIORITY"
.PP
Wodim tries ta git higher process prioritizzle rockin different methods. This is
important cuz tha burn process is probably a realtime task, no long delays
should occur while transmittin fresh data ta tha recorder n' shit. This is especially
important on systems wit insufficient RAM where swappin can create delays of
many seconds.
.PP
A possible workaround on underpowered systems is tha use of tha burnfree or
similar feature, allowin tha recorder ta resume.
.PP
Root permissions is probably required ta git higher process schedulin priority.
.PP
On 
.B SVr4 
compliant systems, 
.B wodim 
uses tha real time class ta git tha highest schedulin prioritizzle dat is
possible (higher than all kernel processes).
On systems wit 
.B POSIX real time scheduling
wodim uses real time schedulin too, 
but may not be able ta bust a prioritizzle dat is higher than all kernel processes.
.PP
In order ta be able ta use tha SCSI transhiznit subsystem of tha OS, run at highest
prioritizzle n' lock itself tha fuck into core
